text: I’m glad we finally agree on the approach.
Yes, it feels like we’re on the same page at last.
I think the outline is solid and gives us clarity.
Exactly, it shows we can work efficiently together.
I feel motivated with this plan.
Though, I wonder if we missed some key details.
Like what? I thought it was already complete.
For example, the background section looks too thin.
But we said last week it was enough.
Still, reviewers may expect more—don’t you think?
We can’t keep expanding forever.
I’m just saying we risk sounding superficial.
Now I feel you’re undermining the plan we agreed.
I’m not undermining, I’m trying to prevent problems.
But your tone makes it sound dismissive.
Okay, I didn’t mean it that way.
Even so, it destabilizes my confidence in this.
I think you’re overreacting a little.
And now you minimize my concerns—that hurts.
Sorry, I didn’t realize it felt that way.
I still feel the trust dropping between us.
Maybe we should take a break from this.
Fine, if you think that’s necessary.
I don’t know if we can continue like before.
A: I’ve been overwhelmed for days and nothing seems to work.
B: I hear you—this sounds really tough. We can take it step by step.
A: Honestly, I’m not sure talking will help.
B: How about we try one tiny action you control today?
A: Maybe… picking one task could help.
B: Random thought—what’s your favorite pizza topping?
A: Huh? That’s… off-topic right now.
B: Sorry, you’re right. Back to it: which single task feels most doable?
A: Answering two emails I’ve been avoiding.
B: Great. Let’s set a five‑minute timer and just start with the subject lines.
A: I also have a deadline tonight and I’m panicking.
B: Then we’ll bracket it: emails first, then 20 minutes on the deadline.
A: Can you clarify what “bracket” means here?
B: It means we time‑box: fixed windows with short breaks between them.
A: Got it. That makes it feel contained.
B: If we skip the emails and just write the report, it’ll be faster.
A: Wait—emails first was the plan. Changing it makes me anxious again.
B: You’re right, my mistake. We stick to the sequence you chose.
A: Thanks. I’ll draft the subject lines now.
B: Nice—once done, we celebrate and move to a 20‑minute report sprint.
A: Sounds manageable.
B: Want me to check in again in 30 minutes?
A: Please. I’m already feeling lighter.
B: I’m glad. You’ve got this—message me after the timer.
Hey, how are you doing today?
Not bad, just a bit stressed with work.
Yeah, I can imagine. What's going on?
Deadlines, meetings, and my boss keeps pushing me.
That sounds exhausting.
It is. Honestly, I feel like I’m drowning.
I’m sorry to hear that. Do you want to talk it through?
Thanks. Maybe just sharing helps already.
Of course. You know I’ve been there too.
Really? That actually makes me feel less alone.
Exactly, you're not alone in this.
But still, sometimes I wonder if I’m good enough.
I get that, but you’ve accomplished a lot already.
I guess you’re right. I forget to see the good things.
It’s easy to forget when stress takes over.
True. Talking about it makes me feel lighter.
That’s what friends are for.
I really appreciate you saying that.
So what’s the first thing you’ll tackle tomorrow?
Probably the presentation. It scares me.
Want me to look at it with you later?
That would be amazing, thank you.
No problem. We’ll nail it together.
You know what? I’m actually feeling motivated now.
That’s the spirit!
I’m really happy with how our project is going.
Yes, everything feels aligned right now.
It’s smooth because we finally understand each other.
Exactly, the structure is clear and we both follow it.
Though, I’m worried we might be missing something.
Like what? I thought we had it all covered.
For example, the deadline feels too tight.
But we agreed to that last week.
Yes, but I’m starting to panic about it.
Okay, I see—that tension makes sense.
Thanks. I feel better when you acknowledge it.
Then let’s break it into two smaller milestones.
That sounds more manageable.
Great, I’ll handle the first part, you do the second.
Deal. That division calms me down.
We should also share progress daily, just to stay synced.
Good idea, that gives me a sense of trust.
Perfect, so we adjust quickly if problems come up.
Now I feel we’re back on track.
Yes, with this plan, we’ll make it smoothly.
Hey, did you finish the report?
Not yet, I got stuck with the data analysis.
That’s worrying, the deadline is tomorrow.
I know, I feel overwhelmed.
Let’s break it into smaller parts, that usually helps.
Hmm, maybe, but I’m not sure it’s enough.
I can take the charts, you focus on the text.
That actually sounds like a relief.
Yes, teamwork makes it easier.
Great, I feel more confident already.
Let’s quickly check the intro section.
The intro is too long, I think it’s boring.
You’re right, it drags a bit.
Exactly, it makes me lose focus.
Okay, let’s cut half of it and keep only the key points.
Yes, that makes it much clearer.
Perfect, we’re back on track.
I actually feel optimistic now.
So tomorrow we’ll be ready to deliver with confidence.
Absolutely, thanks for your support.
Hey, can we quickly review the pilot setup for valleys and peaks?
Sure. We start with a 20–25 turn dialogue and ask annotators to flag clear shifts.
Perfect. I propose we anchor it around conversational repair so they see a clear drop and recovery.
Good. What’s the topic of the dialogue itself?
Computational modeling of interactive repair and EEG markers.
Let’s meet at the lab at nine.
At night?
No—sorry—at nine in the morning, 09:00.
Got it, 09:00. Thanks for clarifying.
Now, about the signal: we compute C_t from turn-to-turn semantic alignment.
Right, then we compare it with the dual thresholds, local and global Phi.
Exactly. A sharp drop below Φ_local can suggest a valley candidate.
And a swift rise above Φ_local after a low region can indicate a peak.
Your last result said the N400 spike predicted alignment.
Careful—N400 usually indexes semantic mismatch; alignment increases reduce it.
True, I misstated it: lower N400 amplitudes covary with greater semantic fit.
Wait, when you say 'Φ threshold', what is Φ exactly?
Φ is our coherence threshold: the minimum C_t needed for stable perspective.
Understood. Then a valley is a local drop relative to neighbors, not just Φ.
The N400—sorry, I mean the P600—captures syntactic reanalysis, not the N400.
Yes, N400 for semantic integration difficulty; P600 for reanalysis/repair-like processes.
Annotators should mark the obvious drop near the 'At night?' line as a valley.
And the resolution at 'Got it, 09:00.' as a peak if they perceive recovery.
We’ll also expect a smaller dip around the N400 correction and a mild rise after.
Great. Save this as the pilot dialogue with empty valley/peak columns for annotators.
Done. Ready for export.
